00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:25.519
All right, for those of you who are unfamiliar, here's a quick

00:05:25.519 --> 00:05:29.000
overview of last year's Big Data Bowl competition. So this was

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.480
the competition's fourth year, and the subject was chosen to be

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:36.839
on special teams. Special teams includes plays like punt returns,

00:05:36.839 --> 00:05:41.119
kick returns, field goals, and extra points. We were provided

00:05:41.119 --> 00:05:44.799
data from three NFL seasons, including next gen stats,

00:05:44.799 --> 00:05:48.399
tracking data, PFF, advanced scouting data, and other basic

00:05:48.399 --> 00:05:53.160
stats from the NFL. In total, there were $100,000 in prizes

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:57.480
awarded to three college and five open finalists. And then we

00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:00.640
were lucky enough to be named the grand champions out of these

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:01.679
eight finalists.

00:06:02.279 --> 00:06:05.679
So now for a bit of inspiration behind the project. This is an

00:06:05.679 --> 00:06:09.880
entry into this year's 2022 Big Data Bowl by Zach Rogers, and

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:13.200
this gives good motivation for our work. It puts you in the

00:06:13.200 --> 00:06:16.559
shoes of the punt returner. If you can imagine that you are the

00:06:16.559 --> 00:06:18.959
punt returner, what should you look for after receiving the

00:06:18.959 --> 00:06:22.519
punt? Our project aimed to answer a couple of these main

00:06:22.519 --> 00:06:26.160
questions. So firstly, are returners making good decisions

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:29.920
to increase yards? Are they finding optimal gathering? Are

00:06:30.279 --> 00:06:33.880
they finding optimal gaps, assessing tackle risk? And are

00:06:33.880 --> 00:06:37.880
they using their teammates and following their blocks? Secondly,

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:40.359
we wanted to determine who was the best at evaluating their

00:06:40.359 --> 00:06:43.760
decision. Could we rank returners, which could then

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:47.320
allow coaches to determine the best returners based on a given

00:06:47.320 --> 00:06:51.519
situation? Now I'll toss it over to Robin and Brendan, and we'll

00:06:51.519 --> 00:06:53.880
go over some more details of the project.

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:58.920
Cool, thank you. So now that we know what the punt returner

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:03.000
needs to consider, and what our goals are, we want to be able to

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:07.559
find show the best path to the end zone, like we see in green

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:11.679
on the figure here. The observed path is shown in black, the

00:07:11.679 --> 00:07:15.279
returner and his team are shown in yellow and gray, while the

00:07:15.279 --> 00:07:17.079
kick team players are shown in pink.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:20.880
So the first step in building our optimal path is to find gaps

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:23.760
in the kick teams coverage. For this we use the Lonnie

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:27.040
triangulation. So this is a mesh like structure that connects the

00:07:27.040 --> 00:07:31.600
points such that all players in the hall are all connected to

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:35.559
form triangles with no lines overlapping. This is shown with

00:07:35.559 --> 00:07:39.440
the purple lines between any two kick team players. And to

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:42.239
account for the punt returner going around all the points,

00:07:42.239 --> 00:07:45.679
we need to find gaps in the kick team's coverage. So for this,

00:07:45.679 --> 00:07:48.200
with the punt returner going around all the players and

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:51.959
towards the sidelines, we add new gaps that connect the players

00:07:51.959 --> 00:07:54.920
on the outside of the hall to the boundaries of the zone of

00:07:54.920 --> 00:07:58.279
interest. So these are shown by the vertical and horizontal

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:02.399
purple lines here. Some of the interesting packages we use are

00:08:02.399 --> 00:08:05.200
tri-mesh and neighbors from the tri-pack family.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:12.320
And now that we have these windows to find that the punt

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:15.160
returner can move through on his way towards the end zone, we

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:18.200
want to move towards quantifying the pressure along

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:20.799
each of these windows. And we do this using our penalized

00:08:20.799 --> 00:08:24.040
expected arrival time algorithm. To give a bit of visual

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:27.519
intuition behind this algorithm, if you look at that heat line

00:08:27.519 --> 00:08:30.679
in the top left of the plot here, you can see that towards

00:08:30.679 --> 00:08:33.840
the sideline, it's colored green, indicating that there's

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:36.640
a lot of open space there. And it's going to take the members

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:39.840
of the kicking team a long time to get to that position. While

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:42.840
as you move closer and closer to where all the players are, you

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:46.200
that it goes from green to yellow to red, indicating that

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:49.760
there's more pressure and less time for the punt returner to

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:54.280
move through that area. And to kind of formalize this a little

00:08:54.280 --> 00:08:57.000
bit more, the goal of this algorithm is to obtain the

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.960
minimum time we expect it to take a member of the kicking

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:04.400
team in red here to reach a target location as indicated by

00:09:04.400 --> 00:09:07.200
the X here. And we're going to take a bunch of different target

00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:11.440
locations. But let's just focus on this single spot right here.

00:09:12.119 --> 00:09:15.039
So with that target location, we're going to look at every

00:09:15.039 --> 00:09:18.400
kicking team player on the field or every player in red, that's

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:23.080
trying to stop the punt returner from moving forward. And let's

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:27.559
say we just look at number 97, for example, to start off here.

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:30.880
So with number 97, what we're going to do is we're going to

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:33.640
create a straight line connecting him to that target

00:09:33.640 --> 00:09:37.280
location. And once we do that, we're going to find all blockers

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:40.799
that we can project onto this straight line at a 90 degree

00:09:40.799 --> 00:09:44.599
angle. And that's going to sort of be all of the blockers that

00:09:44.599 --> 00:09:47.679
can really reasonably impede his path from getting to that target

00:09:47.679 --> 00:09:52.919
location. So here we have number 82 and number 19. And for these

00:09:52.919 --> 00:09:56.039
blockers, we're going to take two different measurements. So

00:09:56.039 --> 00:09:58.559
first, we're going to take the length of that projection from

00:09:58.559 --> 00:10:02.440
82 to the straight line, as indicated by D1 here. And that's

00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:05.799
going to be a measure of the lateral distance from the kicking

00:10:05.799 --> 00:10:09.479
team player. And then we're going to take the distance from

00:10:09.479 --> 00:10:13.119
number 97 to that projection. And that's going to be

00:10:13.119 --> 00:10:17.119
indicated by D2 here. And that's sort of the forward distance

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:21.679
from the kicking team player to the blocker. And with these two

00:10:21.679 --> 00:10:24.400
measurements, we're going to attribute time penalties for

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:27.719
each of the blockers using what we call a projected Gaussian

00:10:27.719 --> 00:10:32.200
kernel. And that's characterized by the equation right here and

00:10:32.239 --> 00:10:35.719
the heat map below. And sort of what we're trying to do here is

00:10:35.719 --> 00:10:39.359
to create an equation where we're kind of accurately

00:10:39.359 --> 00:10:44.719
capturing how much a blocker is likely to impede a member of the

00:10:44.719 --> 00:10:48.359
kicking team's path to that target location. Right, so you

00:10:48.359 --> 00:10:51.200
can see here that when you're very close and right in front of

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:53.880
number 97, you're going to impose a very high penalty.

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:57.400
Whereas as we move further and further out, you can be a bit

00:10:57.400 --> 00:11:01.640
more lateral from the kicking team player or from number 97.

00:11:02.119 --> 00:11:05.760
But you you have less of a penalty overall, right? Because

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:09.960
if you're say you're right in front of number 97, like one foot

00:11:09.960 --> 00:11:14.159
forward from him, but five feet to the left, then you're less

00:11:14.159 --> 00:11:19.679
likely to actually catch him or impede him than if you're, say,

00:11:19.760 --> 00:11:24.280
10 feet forward from him and five feet to the left. And once

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:27.119
we assign these blocker penalties, we're going to simply

00:11:27.119 --> 00:11:31.479
add them all up. So with number 19, and number 82, they impose

00:11:31.479 --> 00:11:37.520
a 0.54 and 0.31 second penalty on number 97, respectively,

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:41.080
giving us a total penalty of 0.85 seconds by these two

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:45.039
blockers. Then we're going to calculate the expected time to

00:11:45.039 --> 00:11:49.440
the target location for number 97, given that he runs at a

00:11:49.440 --> 00:11:52.359
straight line speed of seven yards per second, and that's

00:11:52.359 --> 00:11:56.719
going to be 2.34 seconds. Then we add these two values up. So

00:11:56.719 --> 00:11:59.559
the time that we expect him to take to get to that target

00:11:59.559 --> 00:12:04.239
location unimpeded as 2.34, and the blocker penalty that we

00:12:04.239 --> 00:12:08.840
expect to happen as 0.85. And that's going to give us 3.19

00:12:08.840 --> 00:12:13.599
seconds for number 97 to that target. And we're going to

00:12:13.599 --> 00:12:16.200
repeat this process over and over for every member of the

00:12:16.200 --> 00:12:19.239
kicking team. And on the left here, you can see we have a

00:12:19.239 --> 00:12:23.000
little table with the top few players here. And number 17 is

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.440
the quickest to get to that target location at 0.92 seconds

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:29.960
in this in this case. And that's sort of that's going to

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:34.119
be our measure of the time we expect a member of the kicking

00:12:34.119 --> 00:12:37.599
team to get to that location, or our penalized expected arrival

00:12:37.599 --> 00:12:41.239
time. And we're going to repeat this process over and over for

00:12:41.239 --> 00:12:44.760
up to 20 evenly spaced points along each of these windows. So

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:48.760
on that, so that's where we get that sort of heat line map on

00:12:48.760 --> 00:12:51.960
the left here, where you can see where we're basically just

00:12:51.960 --> 00:12:54.719
taking a bunch of different targets, and we're smoothing

00:12:54.719 --> 00:12:58.919
them out to get a nice, these nice kind of color transitions

00:12:58.919 --> 00:13:01.960
over each of the windows. And now I'll pass it back over to

00:13:01.960 --> 00:13:06.000
Robin to talk about how we go from this penalized expected

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.719
arrival time measure to actually finding the optimal path through

00:13:09.719 --> 00:13:10.479
the menus.

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:16.159
Great, so now that we have our mesh structure and a waiting

00:13:16.159 --> 00:13:19.400
system for it, we need to find a way to get the punt returner to

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:23.400
the end zone. And to do this, we use the A star search algorithm.

00:13:25.719 --> 00:13:28.880
So it works a little bit like a GPS and just finds the safest

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:32.599
route while avoiding traffic. Our algorithm looks at a

00:13:32.599 --> 00:13:35.880
heuristic function, which defines how many yards are

00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:39.880
remaining from the target to the end zone, and a cost function.

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:43.520
This cost function describes the distance between the punt

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:46.919
returner and the target, the danger associated with the

00:13:46.919 --> 00:13:50.960
target point, as well as how risky of a target the punt

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:55.679
returner may be willing to consider traveling to. The

00:13:55.679 --> 00:13:59.320
algorithm looks at various possible routes and restarts

00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:02.919
whenever the total of the heuristic and cost function

00:14:02.919 --> 00:14:09.200
become too large. We can set a few constants to help us with

00:14:09.200 --> 00:14:12.039
the trade off between risk and reward for the punt returner.

00:14:12.440 --> 00:14:15.479
So today, we're going to really focus on the alpha term and see

00:14:15.479 --> 00:14:19.359
how changing it might adjust this trade off between risk and

00:14:19.359 --> 00:14:25.280
reward. So for our submission, if you have the chance to look

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:30.080
at it, we used alpha of 0.5. So we consider this to be a good

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:33.359
mixture of risk and reward for a punt returner wanting to gain

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:37.520
yards while still avoiding the tackle, avoiding injury, stuff

00:14:37.520 --> 00:14:41.840
like that. If we were to change alpha to be one, the path

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:45.400
considers only yards remaining to the end zone with no care of

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:48.119
the danger of being tackled. So this would mean that you're

00:14:48.119 --> 00:14:50.799
going basically straight to the end zone and hopefully that you

00:14:50.799 --> 00:14:54.280
can push everyone out of the way. And then setting alpha to

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:58.320
zero finds the safest path available without considering if

00:14:58.320 --> 00:15:02.200
it's really going to bring you closer to the end zone. So this

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:05.479
typically will send you along the sidelines and push you the

00:15:05.479 --> 00:15:06.159
rest of the way.

00:15:08.760 --> 00:15:11.599
And now that we have this optimal path defined, let's just

00:15:11.599 --> 00:15:15.400
take a look at a case here where we set alpha equal to 0.5. And

00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:19.359
we want to compare the optimal path versus our the actual

00:15:19.359 --> 00:15:22.520
observed path for the punt returner. And to do that, we

00:15:22.520 --> 00:15:25.559
look over the next five yards for each of the path. So as you

00:15:25.559 --> 00:15:28.239
can see on the top right here in the visual, we have sort of the

00:15:28.239 --> 00:15:32.320
highlighted black and green line over the next five yards. And we

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:36.479
want to calculate the crochet distance over this time. And

00:15:36.479 --> 00:15:39.440
crochet distance is a measure of difference between two paths

00:15:39.679 --> 00:15:42.559
where essentially intuitively you could think of it as one

00:15:42.559 --> 00:15:46.000
path being a man, the other path being a dog. And the

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.280
crochet distance is the minimum length of a leash you need to

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:54.359
traverse from one end of the paths to the other end. And you

00:15:54.359 --> 00:15:59.000
can see visually a bit of visual intuition behind this. With the

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.000
blue lines here, you can see that sort of like steps along

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.760
each of these paths. And the teal line there is another step,

00:16:05.760 --> 00:16:08.760
but it's just the step where the length is maximized. And that's

00:16:08.760 --> 00:16:11.039
sort of the minimum length of a leash that you would need to

00:16:11.039 --> 00:16:15.919
traverse from both ends. And with this crochet distance, we

00:16:15.919 --> 00:16:19.599
also have to take into account a couple of other things. Just in

00:16:19.599 --> 00:16:21.960
case there are cases where there's less than five yards

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:25.719
remaining in either the observed or the optimal path. So if there

00:16:25.719 --> 00:16:28.159
aren't, so if both paths are more than five yards, then we

00:16:28.159 --> 00:16:30.679
just simply calculate the crochet distance. And that's

00:16:30.679 --> 00:16:35.080
sort of our measure of deviation from the optimal path in that

00:16:35.080 --> 00:16:40.039
moment. But if either of the paths are between one and five

00:16:40.039 --> 00:16:43.320
yards, then we're going to multiply the crochet distance

00:16:43.320 --> 00:16:46.799
by five and divide it by the minimum of those two, the

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:50.039
minimum length of those two paths to sort of scale up and

00:16:50.039 --> 00:16:53.960
account for the fact that that path, we aren't really seeing a

00:16:53.960 --> 00:16:57.080
full five yard movement. So we're trying to kind of

00:16:57.080 --> 00:17:00.559
counteract that. And if there's less than one yard on either of

00:17:00.559 --> 00:17:03.039
the paths, then we omit the calculation since we don't

00:17:03.039 --> 00:17:06.319
really have enough information to see how the punt return was

00:17:06.319 --> 00:17:11.680
moving relative to the optimal path. And yeah, with with this

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:14.359
optimal path algorithm, we also just wanted to give a quick

00:17:14.359 --> 00:17:17.119
shout out to some of the key R functions that really helped us

00:17:17.119 --> 00:17:21.640
in this process. So first up nest and map are super helpful

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:27.880
for making this whole process very tidy and clean and, and

00:17:27.880 --> 00:17:33.199
being able to apply large scale analysis using very complex

00:17:33.199 --> 00:17:36.920
operations within just a single data frame. So nest essentially

00:17:36.920 --> 00:17:41.160
allows you to group say you want to group the data by moment or

00:17:41.160 --> 00:17:44.560
by each frame of the play where a frame is simply just a moment

00:17:44.560 --> 00:17:48.880
in time. But you have 20 rows of player locations. If you group

00:17:48.880 --> 00:17:52.839
by the play or by the frame, then you can sort of nest the

00:17:52.839 --> 00:17:57.319
data into a column of data frames, which includes all of

00:17:57.319 --> 00:18:00.479
the player locations. So you have one row per frame. But

00:18:00.479 --> 00:18:04.319
within that row, you have sort of a data frame of all of the

00:18:04.319 --> 00:18:08.400
player locations. Then with the map function, you can start

00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:12.479
applying different functions to that data. So you can apply

00:18:13.319 --> 00:18:18.040
basically functions to find the windows for the punt return to

00:18:18.040 --> 00:18:21.119
move through or calculate the penalized expected arrival time

00:18:21.160 --> 00:18:25.880
or find the optimal path with the A star algorithm using this

00:18:25.880 --> 00:18:30.000
map function all within one data frame. And future map is just

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:33.280
an evolution beyond that where you can parallelize the code. So

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:37.199
it runs a bit quicker. And dplyr, of course, was super

00:18:37.199 --> 00:18:39.680
helpful for us just with building out sort of a tiny

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:43.640
verse pipeline with key functions like mutate, select and

00:18:43.640 --> 00:18:47.560
filters, and also the pipe operator making the code nice

00:18:47.560 --> 00:18:51.719
and sleek. Then of course, our all of our plots here are made

00:18:51.719 --> 00:18:56.560
with ggplot and gganimate. And it's those packages are just

00:18:56.560 --> 00:18:59.880
super awesome for making very nice, aesthetically pleasing

00:18:59.880 --> 00:19:01.359
plots with very little effort.

